The paper deals with external memory data structures, specifically priority queues and buffered repository trees, which are classic topics in data structures (cs.DS). The algorithms presented in the paper have applications to graph algorithms, such as single-source shortest paths, depth-first search, and breadth-first search, which fall under the category of graph theory (cs.GR). The paper also discusses the I/O complexity of the algorithms, which is a common topic in the area of external memory algorithms (cs.DM). The use of block size and main memory size as parameters suggests that the paper may also fall under the category of parallel and distributed computing (cs.DC). Finally, the paper presents new results and algorithms, which could also place it under the category of algorithms (cs.AL).
